links.title: FireEye Hack Spreads to SolarWinds as U.S. Agencies Are Breached
links.description: The cyber attack on the security-software firm FireEye that was disclosed last week appears to be affecting potentially thousands of corporate and government systems, including U.S. federal agencies. An important wrinkle disclosed by FireEye (ticker: FEYE) late Sunday is that the attack has a newly disclosed vector: a tainted update to widely used IT-management software sold by the Austin-based software company SolarWinds (SWI).

messages.body:
US IT company $SWI said fewer than 18K of its customers had downloaded a compromised software update which allowed suspected Russian hackers to spy on global businesses & govts unnoticed for almost 9 months.

US Dept of Homeland Security issued an emergency warning on Sunday, ordering users to disconnect & disable SolarWinds software which it said had been compromised by “malicious actors.”

Reuters reported that suspected Russian hackers had used hijacked software updates to break into multiple American government agencies, including the Treasury & Commerce departments.

SolarWinds Corp said it believed the attack was the work of an “outside nation state” that inserted malicious code into updates of its Orion network management software issued between March and June this year.

It is unclear whether a breach last week of security vendor $FEYE was also linked to SolarWinds.

Russia denied having any connection to the attacks.
